rows.content:
For Future Research about risk behavior, the institute of biological psychology at Kiel University currently creates a new inventory, which should reflect common risk situations. In the following, you will be informed about the content, the procedure and special features of this study, handling data, the voluntary nature of your participation, your right to ask questions as well as possible risks that go along with participation.

The study is being conducted as part of the Bachelor's thesis of Georg Leistenschneider. Prof. Dr. Julian Keil, Institute for psychology at Kiel University, is responsible for the supervision and supervision of the study.

Psychology Students can collect 0,75 subject hours at the study directory for participation.


Content:
Based on this survey, we attempt to create an Inventory on participant's everyday risk situations. This inventory will then form a more everyday approach to investigate the risk behavior of individuals. The Personal Risk Inventory by Hocker (2000) serves as a basis. This will be validated with another sample in a later part of the study, together with the data collected here.

Procedure:
At first, you will be asked to indicate some demographic data. By pressing the 'Next' button, you will then be taken to a page, where you will have the opportunity to list some repeated risk situations of the last two weeks. Please use the format provided. The decision alternatives should then be rated on a Likert scale from 1 (not risky at all) to 7 (extremely risky). How you have decided is not of interest here. Please feel free to add as many situations as you can think of. Answering all questions will take approximately 10-45 minutes.
Please complete the instructions during the study to the best of your knowledge and belief. There are no right or wrong answers.

Risks:
Except for the risks you describe, the participation is not connected with any further risks for you.

Data protection:
By agreeing to participate in the study mentioned above, you agree that the study director and the employees mentioned above may collect and process your personal data for the purpose of the study mentioned above. The collection of the data, as well as the further processing including their evaluation will be carried out at the institute for psychology at Kiel University. In collection, processing and evaluation of the collected data, the persons mentioned in the beginning of this information for study participants. Personal data are, for example, your date of birth, your gender, data related to your physical or mental health or other data collected during your participation in this study. The study director and the staff mentioned above will use your personal data for purposes of administration and implementation of the study as well as for research and statistical evaluation. All data will be processed and saved in encrypted form. This means that all data collected (such as your answers to the questions on the computer) are not linked to your person. In accordance with the legal retention period, all collected data (see above) will be stored for a maximum of 10 years (on a password-protected PC) and then destroyed. You can withdraw your consent to the further processing of the data collected in the course of the study mentioned above and demand their complete deletion. You have the right to access all personal data about you held by the study director. You also have the right to have any inaccuracies in your personal data corrected. In this case, please contact the study director directly. You can find the address and phone number of the study director on this page. Please note that the results of this study may be published in a scientific journal while your identity will remain anonymous.

Voluntariness:
Your participation is voluntary. Only if you agree, you can be included in the study. You can withdraw your consent to participate in the study at any time informally and without giving reasons. This will not involve any disadvantages for you. The same applies to the cancellation of your participation in the study and the revocation of your consent as well as in the event of a disagreement to the further processing of the data.

Do you have any questions? Then you are welcome to contact me, Georg Leistenschneider, or the study directory.

rows.title: Hello!
rows.content:
Now please describe (at least 2) repeating situations from your everyday life during the last weeks, in which you have made a decision unter a risk. Then please rate on a scale from 1 (not risky at all) to 7 (extremely risky), how you would estimate the situation. Here it is not important, how you have decided in the end. The situation may also have occurred in various contexts (e.g. health, finance, social, law etc.)

For better understanding I have prepared two examples for you:


1) I wanted to visit a close relative in hospital and managed to get away from work during rush hour. As usual, the visitor parking lot is full and I know that at this time of day I have to look for a parking space for at least 15 minutes. I could park in the employee parking lot, but these are checked by the public order office from time to time and sometimes cars are towed away. I had to decide between two options:

A| Park in the visitor parking lot
B| Park in the employee parking lot.

Rating A: not risky at all
Rating B: rather risky


2) I overslept and risked being late for an important video conference. I was still in my pyjamas and a bit grumpy as I had not had breakfast yet. So I was able to decide if I wanted to...

A| turn on the computer as soon as possible.
B| get ready first.

Rating A: a little risky
Rating B: extremely risky
